<h2>Fieldset Cascade</h2>
<p>Adding <code>disabled</code> to a <code>&lt;fieldset&gt;</code> disables every form control inside it, regardless of nesting depth. This is the cleanest way to disable an entire section of a form with a single attribute.</p>

<code-block language="html" label="Disabled fieldset">{{ fieldsetExample | escape }}</code-block>

<p>The <code>&lt;legend&gt;</code> element inside a disabled fieldset remains interactive. Any form controls inside the <code>&lt;legend&gt;</code> are not disabled by the fieldset cascade. This is intentional — the legend is considered a label, not a form control.</p>

<h2>Form Submission</h2>
<p>Disabled controls are excluded from <code>FormData</code> entirely. Their name/value pairs are not sent to the server. This catches developers off guard when they disable a field to make it "read-only" and then wonder why the value is missing.</p>

<code-block language="html" label="Submission exclusion">{{ submissionExample | escape }}</code-block>

<p>If you need the value submitted but non-editable, use <a href="/docs/attributes/readonly/"><code>readonly</code></a> or pair the disabled field with a <code>&lt;input type="hidden"&gt;</code> that carries the value.</p>

<h2>Styling</h2>
<p>Browsers apply a default dimmed appearance to disabled controls. Use the <code>:disabled</code> and <code>:enabled</code> pseudo-classes for custom styling.</p>

